<p>New Hampshire presents an excellent opportunity for both solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems, making it an ideal state for homeowners looking to reduce their energy costs and carbon footprint. With an average of 4.1 peak sun hours per day, the Granite State receives sufficient solar irradiance to make solar installations highly productive and cost-effective. Despite common misconceptions about solar performance in northern climates, New Hampshire's cold, clear winter days actually enhance solar panel efficiency, while the state's moderate summer temperatures prevent the performance losses seen in extremely hot climates.</p>

<p>The economics for solar and HVAC upgrades in New Hampshire are particularly compelling due to the state's relatively high electricity rates, which average 19.6¬¢ per kilowatt-hour - significantly above the national average of approximately 16¬¢/kWh. Eversource, the state's primary utility provider serving over 500,000 customers, offers various programs and net metering policies that further enhance the financial benefits of solar installations. These high electricity rates mean that every kilowatt-hour of solar energy produced or HVAC efficiency gained translates to substantial savings on monthly utility bills.</p>

<p>New Hampshire's four-season climate, with cold winters requiring substantial heating and increasingly warm summers demanding cooling, creates year-round energy demands that make both solar panels and high-efficiency HVAC systems worthwhile investments. The state's commitment to renewable energy, combined with generous federal tax credits and state-specific incentives, creates a favorable environment for homeowners to make these energy-saving upgrades while significantly reducing their long-term energy costs.</p>

<h2>Solar Panels in New Hampshire</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>New Hampshire's solar resource is more robust than many residents realize, with the state receiving between 3.5 to 4.5 peak sun hours daily depending on location and season. The southern regions of the state, including areas around Nashua, Manchester, and the Seacoast, typically see higher solar production due to their latitude and fewer topographical obstructions. Even northern regions like the White Mountains area maintain viable solar potential, with many installations exceeding expected production forecasts due to snow reflection and the improved efficiency of solar panels in cold temperatures.</p>

<p>A typical residential solar installation in New Hampshire can expect to produce between 1,100 to 1,300 kilowatt-hours per installed kilowatt annually. This means a 6kW system would generate approximately 6,600 to 7,800 kWh per year, which closely matches or exceeds the average New Hampshire household's annual electricity consumption of about 6,200 kWh. The state's net metering policies allow homeowners to receive full retail rate credit for excess solar production, making oversized systems economically beneficial for offsetting seasonal variations in solar production.</p>

<p>Seasonal variation is an important consideration for New Hampshire solar installations. Summer months (June through August) typically produce 40-45% of annual solar generation, while winter months (December through February) account for only 15-20% of annual production. However, this seasonal pattern aligns reasonably well with typical household energy usage patterns, where air conditioning loads in summer are offset by higher heating demands in winter. Ground-mounted systems, while more expensive initially, can be particularly effective in New Hampshire as they can be positioned for optimal snow shedding and year-round solar access.</p>

