<h2>HVAC Systems in New Hampshire</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>New Hampshire's continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, with heating degree days ranging from 6,000 to 8,000 annually depending on location, and cooling degree days typically between 400 to 800. This means heating represents the dominant HVAC load, often accounting for 60-70% of total annual energy consumption in typical homes. Winter temperatures regularly drop below 0¬∞F in many areas, requiring heating systems capable of maintaining comfort during extended cold periods while operating efficiently across a wide temperature range.</p>

<p>The increasing frequency of summer temperatures above 85¬∞F has made air conditioning more of a necessity rather than a luxury in New Hampshire. However, the relatively short cooling season means that cooling equipment often operates at part-load conditions, making variable-capacity systems particularly attractive for their ability to maintain comfort while minimizing energy consumption during moderate weather conditions.</p>

<p>Humidity control is another important consideration, particularly during New Hampshire's humid summers. High-efficiency HVAC systems with variable-speed components excel at moisture removal during part-load conditions, improving both comfort and indoor air quality. In winter, proper humidity control helps prevent issues with dry air while maintaining energy efficiency. Heat pump systems have become increasingly popular in New Hampshire, with modern cold-climate heat pumps capable of providing efficient heating even at temperatures well below 0¬∞F.</p>

