<h2>New Hampshire Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>New Hampshire offers a comprehensive suite of incentives that significantly improve the economics of both solar panel installations and high-efficiency HVAC systems. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) remains the most significant incentive, allowing homeowners to deduct 30% of their total solar installation costs from their federal taxes through 2032. This credit applies to the full system cost, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, and can be carried forward if it exceeds tax liability in the installation year.</p>

<p>The state of New Hampshire provides additional support through its Renewable Energy Rebate Program, offering rebates up to \$3,500 for residential solar installations. This program, administered by the New Hampshire Public Utilities Commission, provides \$0.75 per watt for systems up to 5kW, with additional incentives available for systems that include battery storage. The program also offers enhanced rebates for moderate-income households, making solar more accessible across different economic levels.</p>

<p>Eversource, New Hampshire's largest utility provider, operates the Energy Star Homes Program and offers rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment. These rebates include up to \$1,200 for ENERGY STAR certified air source heat pumps, up to \$5,000 for geothermal heat pump systems, and up to \$400 for high-efficiency central air conditioning systems. The utility also provides financing options through its on-bill recovery program, allowing customers to pay for efficiency upgrades through their monthly utility bills with terms up to 12 years.</p>

<p>Additional local incentives may be available through municipal programs and the New Hampshire Saves program, which offers low-interest financing for energy efficiency improvements. Property tax exemptions for solar installations ensure that adding solar panels won't increase property tax assessments, while net metering policies guarantee full retail rate credit for excess solar production. These combined incentives can reduce the effective cost of solar installations by 40-50% and HVAC upgrades by 20-30%.</p>

