    <p>Solar panel costs in New Hampshire typically range from \$2.75 to \$3.25 per watt before incentives, making a typical 7kW residential system cost between \$19,250 and \$22,750 before applying the federal tax credit. After the 30% federal tax credit and state rebates, homeowners can expect to pay between \$12,000 and \$16,000 for a complete installation. The exact cost depends on factors including roof complexity, equipment selection, local permitting requirements, and installer pricing. Higher-end systems with premium panels and optimizers may cost slightly more but often provide better long-term value through increased production and longer warranties.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What SEER rating is recommended for New Hampshire?</h3>
    <p>For New Hampshire's climate, SEER ratings of 16-18 typically provide the best balance of efficiency and cost-effectiveness for central air conditioning systems. While higher SEER ratings (20+) are available, the relatively short cooling season in most of New Hampshire means the additional cost may not be justified by energy savings alone. However, for heat pump systems that provide both heating and cooling, higher efficiency ratings (SEER 18+ and HSPF 9.5+) are often worthwhile due to their year-round operation. The key is to consider both SEER for cooling efficiency and HSPF (Heating Seasonal Performance Factor) for heating efficiency when selecting heat pump systems.</p>
  </div>
  
